%% Abstract
\begin{abstract}
High-precision transit surveys such as \textit{Kepler} and \textit{TESS} 
struggle to distinguish genuine planetary signals from false positives 
caused by non-stationary noise. Traditional SNR metrics often overestimate 
significance in high-variance regions, producing inflated false-alarm 
rates. To address this, we introduce the Logarithmic Signal-to-Noise 
Ratio with Adjusted Statistics (Log-SNRAS) as a computationally efficient 
post-detection vetting filter designed to penalize variance inhomogeneity. 
Unlike computationally expensive deep learning models, Log-SNRAS utilizes 
a logarithmic damping function based on the normalized dispersion contrast 
($\psi$), providing an interpretable solution with linear time complexity 
($\mathcal{O}(N)$). We validated this metric through a comprehensive 
benchmarking study across 151 curated light-curve segments, specifically 
selected to include adversarial heteroscedastic examples alongside 
validated planetary transits. On the present curated benchmark, Log-SNRAS 
achieved the highest AUC of 0.744 among the tested SNR-based metrics, 
outperforming commonly used SNR baselines including P-SNR ($0.667$), 
T-SNR ($0.594$), and B-SNR ($0.585$). Crucially, Log-SNRAS maintains 
discriminative stability in high-noise regimes where standard robust 
estimators exhibit inverse performance ($AUC < 0.5$). Because the 
confirmed class is dominated by segments from a single stable host 
(TIC~261136679), these results should be interpreted as proof-of-concept 
performance estimates on the present adversarial benchmark rather than 
definitive mission-wide generalization metrics. By transitioning from a 
depth-only detection paradigm to a variance-aware filtering mechanism, 
Log-SNRAS offers a scalable tool for automating false-positive rejection 
in large-scale transit pipelines.
\end{abstract}
