\section{Introduction} \label{sec:intro}

The era of space-based photometry, initiated by the \textit{Kepler} mission \citep{borucki2010} and continued by the Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite (\textit{TESS}) \citep{ricker2014}, has revolutionized our understanding of planetary systems. The detection of exoplanet candidates relies heavily on automated pipeline algorithms that search for periodic dips in stellar flux \citep{jenkins2016, twicken2018}. A critical component of these pipelines is the vetting process, which distinguishes genuine astrophysical signals from false positives caused by instrumental artifacts, stellar variability, or background eclipsing binaries \citep{coughlin2016, mccauliff2015, shallue2018}. \textcolor{blue}{With \textit{TESS} now delivering $> 300,000$ light curves per sector and upcoming missions such as PLATO expected to increase this volume by an order of magnitude, scalable vetting tools that operate in linear time ($\mathcal{O}(N)$) have become essential.}


However, real observational data are often plagued by `heteroscedastic' noise—localized variance instabilities caused by focus drifts, thermal jitters, or cosmic ray hits \citep{christiansen2012}. These artifacts often mimic the depth of a transit while exhibiting a chaotic statistical texture. Standard robust metrics, such as the Robust SNR (R-SNR) or the Pont SNR (P-SNR), attempt to mitigate outliers but often fail to penalize high-amplitude non-stationary noise effectively.  \textcolor{blue}{For instance, the widely used Robust SNR actually performs worse than chance ($AUC = 0.441$) on high-variance artifacts, succumbing to an ``inverse performance'' regime that directly motivates the need for a variance-penalizing metric from the very beginning.}
