In this work, we address this limitation by introducing a novel vetting metric: the \textbf{Logarithmic Signal-to-Noise Ratio with Adjusted Statistics (Log-SNRAS)}. \textcolor{blue}{We introduce Log-SNRAS as a computationally efficient post-detection vetting filter.} Unlike traditional methods that treat noise as a static background value, Log-SNRAS incorporates a dynamic damping term derived from the dispersion contrast ($\psi$) between the in-transit and out-of-transit windows. This formulation empowers the metric to `sense' the morphological stability of a signal. By applying a logarithmic penalty to signals exhibiting significant variance inflation, Log-SNRAS acts as a variance-aware filtering mechanism.

We validate this approach through a comprehensive multi-metric benchmarking study using a curated adversarial dataset ($N=151$). Log-SNRAS achieves the highest AUC of 0.744 among the tested metrics, significantly outperforming commonly used SNR baselines such as 
P-SNR (0.667) and T-SNR (0.594). Notably, we expose a critical failure mode in standard robust estimators (R-SNR), which succumb to an "inverse performance" regime ($AUC=0.441$) when vetted against high-variance stellar artifacts.

\textcolor{blue}{The present work has three specific objectives:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(i)] To derive a variance-stabilized metric that penalizes heteroscedasticity.
    \item[(ii)] To benchmark it against established SNR estimators on an adversarial dataset.
    \item[(iii)] To demonstrate its utility through real \textit{Kepler} and \textit{TESS} case studies.
\end{enumerate}}


\subsection{Operational Use Case: Vetting vs. Discovery}
It is crucial to clarify the operational scope of Log-SNRAS. This metric is designed specifically for the \textbf{vetting stage} (post-detection reliability assessment), not the \textbf{search stage} (initial signal discovery). Standard search algorithms, such as Box Least Squares (BLS) \citep{kovacs2002} or Transit Planet Search (TPS) \citep{jenkins2016}, are optimized to maximize detection sensitivity, often at the cost of accepting high false-alarm rates from instrumental noise. Log-SNRAS is not intended to replace these search grids. Instead, it functions as an orthogonal \textbf{reliability filter} applied to the candidate list generated by the search pipeline. By re-ranking candidates based on their variance stability, Log-SNRAS aims to automate the rejection of high-SNR artifacts that would otherwise clog the candidate validation queue.
\medskip
\textcolor{blue}{\textbf{Key Strengths:} The Log-SNRAS framework is distinguished by three core advantages: (i) theoretical groundedness via Bayesian consistency, (ii) extreme computational efficiency ($\mathcal{O}(N)$), and (iii) diagnostic stability in adversarial noise regimes where traditional robust estimators frequently exhibit inverse performance.}
\textcolor{blue}{The remainder of this paper is organized as follows: Section 2 details the mathematical formulation of Log-SNRAS and the proposed three-tier vetting system. Section 3 presents the experimental setup and performance benchmarks. Section 4 provides condensed case studies on adversarial targets. Section 5 discusses computational efficiency and limitations, and Section 6 concludes the study.}
% ================================================================== %
\section{Derivation of the \textcolor{blue}{Log-SNRAS} Metric} \label{sec:derivation}

Standard transit detection algorithms typically rely on a Signal-to-Noise Ratio (SNR) definition that assumes homoscedasticity within the observation window. The classical SNR for a box-shaped transit is given by:
\begin{equation}
    \text{SNR}_{\text{trad}} = \frac{\delta}{\sigma_{\text{out}}} \sqrt{N},
    \label{eq:snr_trad}
\end{equation}
where $\delta$ is the depth of the transit, $\sigma_{\text{out}}$ is the standard deviation of the out-of-transit flux, and $N$ is the number of in-transit data points. Although effective for Gaussian noise, this metric fails when the noise properties change during the transit event (heteroscedasticity).

\subsection{The Logarithmic Stability Penalty}
To robustly distinguish between genuine planetary signals and instrumental artifacts without penalizing high-SNR candidates in active sectors, we introduce the \textcolor{blue}{Log-SNRAS}. Unlike previous quadratic formulations that could be overly aggressive, this metric incorporates a logarithmic penalty term $\mathcal{P}$. We define the normalized variance instability penalty $\mathcal{P}$ as:
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{P}(\sigma_{\text{in}}, \sigma_{\text{out}}) = \ln \left( 1 + \frac{|\sigma_{\text{in}} - \sigma_{\text{out}}|}{\sigma_{\text{out}}} \right),
    \label{eq:penalty}
\end{equation}
where $\sigma_{\text{in}}$ is the standard deviation of the flux within the transit window. \textcolor{blue}{The in-transit window is defined as the interval $\pm T_{\text{dur}}/2$ centered on the mid-transit time from the BLS ephemeris; the out-of-transit window comprises the remaining points after removing a $2 \times T_{\text{dur}}$ buffer on each side.} %
%% [M2 FIX] Clarify notation to resolve ambiguity flagged by Reviewer
We distinguish three related quantities: the normalized dispersion contrast $\psi = |\sigma_{\rm in} - \sigma_{\rm out}|/\sigma_{\rm out}$, the logarithmic penalty $\mathcal{P} = \ln(1 + \psi)$, and the denominator scaling factor $D = 1 + \mathcal{P}$. Thus, $\mathcal{P} \to 0$ and $D \to 1$ in the homoscedastic limit. Note that Table~\ref{tab:dataset_stats} reports the median value of $D$, not $\mathcal{P}$.
%% [END M2 FIX]
This logarithmic formulation ensures that the penalty grows slowly for moderate variance differences (preserving genuine planets with stellar jitter) but scales sufficiently to suppress extreme variance explosions associated with instrumental artifacts.

\subsection{The \textcolor{blue}{Log-SNRAS} Formulation}
The final \textcolor{blue}{Log-SNRAS} metric applies this penalty as a scaling factor in the denominator of the detection equation:
\begin{equation}
    \textcolor{blue}{\boxed{ \text{Log-SNRAS} = \frac{\delta \sqrt{N}}{\sigma_{\text{out}} \left[ 1 + \ln \left( 1 + \frac{|\sigma_{\text{in}} - \sigma_{\text{out}}|}{\sigma_{\text{out}}} \right) \right]} }}
\label{eq:snras}
\end{equation}
We deliberately utilize a difference-based contrast $\psi$ rather than a simple variance ratio (e.g., $\sigma_{in}/\sigma_{out}$) to ensure the metric is centered at zero for stable signals. This formulation aligns with the principle of "Excess Noise": when $\sigma_{in} \approx \sigma_{out}$, the penalty $\mathcal{P} = \ln(1+0)$ vanishes naturally, recovering the optimal matched filter limit without requiring offset corrections.

