\end{figure}

\textcolor{blue}{The derivation of the logarithmic penalty via a Lomax prior ensures Bayesian consistency, providing a formal statistical foundation for the variance-stabilization mechanism.}

\subsection{Mathematical Proof of Convergence}
To rigorously validate the behavior of the improved \textcolor{blue}{Log-SNRAS}, we analyze its limits under two critical conditions.

\subsubsection*{Case 1: The Homoscedastic Limit (Ideal Planet)}
Consider a genuine planetary transit where the noise properties remain stable across the light curve boundary, i.e. $\sigma_{\text{in}} \to \sigma_{\text{out}}$. The penalty term becomes:
\begin{equation}
    \lim_{\sigma_{\text{in}} \to \sigma_{\text{out}}} \mathcal{P} = \ln(1 + 0) = 0.
\end{equation}
Substituting this into Eq. \ref{eq:snras}:
\begin{equation}
    \lim_{\sigma_{\text{in}} \to \sigma_{\text{out}}} \textcolor{blue}{\text{Log-SNRAS}} = \text{SNR}_{\text{trad}}.
\end{equation}
\textbf{Result:} \textcolor{blue}{Log-SNRAS} converges exactly to the optimal traditional SNR for stable signals, ensuring no loss of sensitivity for real planets.

\subsubsection*{Case 2: The Heteroscedastic Limit (Noise Artifact)}
Consider a scenario where a local noise burst causes the in-transit variance to diverge, i.e. $|\sigma_{\text{in}} - \sigma_{\text{out}}| \to \infty$. The penalty term grows as $\ln(\infty) \to \infty$:
\begin{equation}
    \lim_{| \sigma_{\text{in}} - \sigma_{\text{out}} | \to \infty} \textcolor{blue}{\text{Log-SNRAS}} \to 0.
\end{equation}
\textbf{Proof Result:} As the statistical tension increases, the metric asymptotically approaches zero, effectively vetoing the artifact regardless of the signal depth $\delta$.

\subsection{Automated Vetting Tiers} \label{sec:tiers}
To transition from a continuous penalty metric to actionable vetting decisions, we formalize a three-tier classification system. Rather than relying on arbitrary visual cuts, the boundaries are defined based on the \textbf{Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC)} performance regimes derived in Section \ref{sec:roc}. The thresholds correspond to distinct operational points on the sensitivity curve:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item The lower bound ($\mathcal{P} \le 0.15$) delimits the \textit{High-Fidelity Regime}, optimized to minimize the False Positive Rate (FPR) and prioritize sample purity.
    \item The upper bound ($\mathcal{P} > 0.60$) marks the \textit{Rejection Threshold}, beyond which the signal probability effectively approaches zero due to variance saturation.

\end{enumerate}

\textcolor{blue}{These tiers, empirically calibrated on the present dataset, categorize the targets as follows. Note that these thresholds are specific to the current adversarial catalog and may require re-calibration for new pipelines or missions:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Tier 1: High Fidelity ($\mathcal{P} \leq 0.15$).} \\
    Candidates in this regime exhibit quasi-homoscedastic behavior ($\psi \lesssim 0.16$). The penalty is negligible ($<15\%$), indicating that the signal significance is driven primarily by transit depth rather than noise fluctuations. These are prioritized as "Clean Candidates."

    \item \textbf{Tier 2: Complexity Flags ($0.15 < \mathcal{P} \leq 0.60$).} \\
    This transitional tier captures signals with moderate local instability. While the detection remains significant, the logarithmic penalty suppresses the SNR by $15-60\%$, flagging potential stellar activity or mild instrumental systematics. Manual inspection or centroid analysis is recommended.
    \textcolor{blue}{In terms of pipeline integration, these tiers provide a concrete operational workflow: Tier 1 candidates can be fast-tracked to centroid vetting and atmospheric characterization, Tier 2 candidates are flagged for human-in-the-loop manual inspection, and Tier 3 artifacts are automatically rejected. This triage system is estimated to reduce the human vetting load by 40--60\% in high-noise sectors, directly addressing the scalability bottleneck in current and future missions.}

    \item \textbf{Tier 3: Geometric Veto ($\mathcal{P} > 0.60$).} \\
    Targets exceeding this threshold are dominated by heteroscedastic noise ($\psi \gtrsim 0.8$). The metric aggressively penalizes these signals (suppression $>60\%$), effectively vetoing them as non-stationary artifacts (e.g., cosmic ray hits or sudden pixel sensitivity dropouts) regardless of their raw depth.
\end{itemize}

\textcolor{blue}{\subsection{Reproducibility Statement}
To ensure full transparency and reproducibility, the MATLAB reference implementation (requiring the Statistics and Machine Learning Toolbox), all data validation scripts, and the exact 151-segment dataset are publicly available. Stratified bootstrap resampling ($B=2000$) was performed using a fixed random seed to guarantee identical confidence intervals. The exact release tag used to generate the results in this manuscript, along with data preparation routines, is accessible via the GitHub repository linked in the Data Availability section.}

