\section{Field Performance and Empirical Validation} \label{sec:performance}

To evaluate the discriminatory power of Log-SNRAS under real observational conditions, we conducted a systematic validation campaign.

\subsection{Dataset Construction and Morphological Stratification} \label{sec:dataset_methodology}

The reliability of a vetting metric cannot be assessed through random sampling alone, as the vast majority of light curves in blind surveys are featureless noise. Instead, to rigorously map the operational boundaries of Log-SNRAS, we constructed a \textbf{stratified benchmarking dataset} ($N=151$) designed to cover the full "morphological phase space" of transit signals.

The targets were selected from the \textit{Kepler} and \textit{TESS} archives via the Mikulski Archive for Space Telescopes (MAST) based on three specific inclusion criteria, ensuring a robust stress-test against known failure modes:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{The "Golden Standard" (Positive Control):} We included confirmed, high-fidelity planetary systems (e.g., \textit{Pi Mensae c}, \textit{Kepler-1625 b}) with well-established parameters. These serve as the ground truth for "Metric Transparency," ensuring that the penalty term $\mathcal{P}$ converges to zero for genuine signals.

    \item \textbf{The "Adversarial" Set (Negative Control):} We deliberately selected targets known to confuse traditional estimators, such as:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Disintegrating planets with variable depths (e.g., \textit{KIC 12557548}).
        \item Deep eclipsing binaries mimicking transits (e.g., \textit{KIC 5812701}).
        \item Instrumental artifacts like momentum dumps and rolling bands.
    \end{itemize}
    These targets serve as "stress tests" to verify the metric's ability to trigger penalties in heteroscedastic regimes.

    \item \textbf{The "Boundary" Cases (Edge Cases):} We included signals with low-SNR ($\text{SNR}_{trad} < 10$) and grazing transits to evaluate the metric's sensitivity threshold where signal and noise are comparable.
\end{enumerate}
