\subsection{Diagnostic Stability and ROC Analysis} \label{sec:roc}

To quantify the vetting power under adversarial noise conditions, we performed a comprehensive Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) analysis using the \textbf{complete curated catalog} ($N=151$). \textcolor{blue}{No multiplicity correction was applied because the primary focus is on descriptive ranking of the metrics rather than formal hypothesis testing of individual AUC differences.}
This sample was intentionally designed to be "adversarial," featuring high-amplitude astrophysical false positives that specifically target the weaknesses of traditional statistical estimators.

The diagnostic task focused on discriminating between \textbf{validated planetary transits} and \textbf{heteroscedastic artifacts}. As illustrated in Figure \ref{Fig:ROC}, the results reveal a distinct hierarchy in vetting efficiency. While standard power-based metrics like Traditional SNR (T-SNR) and BLS Power (B-SNR) achieved baseline AUC values of 0.594 and 0.585 respectively, they struggled to consistently separate low-depth planets from high-variance stellar noise.

Notably, the Robust SNR (R-SNR) exhibited an "inverse performance" ($AUC = 0.441$), falling below the random classifier baseline ($AUC = 0.500$). This confirms that traditional robust estimators are systematically biased toward selecting high-amplitude non-stationary noise as planetary candidates, effectively failing in this specific vetting regime.

In stark contrast, \textbf{Log-SNRAS (Proposed)} demonstrates superior diagnostic stability, achieving the highest AUC of \textbf{0.744}. This represents a substantial improvement over the second-best estimator, P-SNR ($AUC=0.667$), and a consistent improvement over the commonly used T-SNR.By introducing a logarithmic penalty coupled with the dispersion contrast ($\psi$), Log-SNRAS successfully decoupled signal depth from noise-induced variance, suppressing the significance of artifacts (e.g., KIC 12644769) while preserving the detection sensitivity for genuine planetary candidates.

