\subsection{Statistical Significance and Robustness Analysis} \label{sec:stats_analysis}

To rigorously assess whether the observed AUC gain represents a systematic improvement rather than a statistical fluctuation, we performed a non-parametric bootstrap analysis. \textcolor{blue}{Stratified bootstrap resampling ($B=2000$) was performed by drawing the full set of 151 light-curve segments with replacement while preserving the Confirmed vs. Artifact class balance.}
Given the adversarial nature of the catalog, the analysis yields a mean AUC advantage for Log-SNRAS of $\Delta \text{AUC} = +0.107$ relative to the Traditional SNR and $+0.217$ relative to the Robust SNR.
Crucially, the 95\% confidence intervals for these improvements strictly exclude zero.
The resulting precise p-value \textcolor{blue}{($p = 0.0004$, two-sided bootstrap test)} decisively rejects the null hypothesis that Log-SNRAS offers no discriminatory advantage. \textcolor{blue}{The bootstrap distribution of $\Delta$AUC remained positive 
under the specified segment-level resampling scheme.}
More importantly, Log-SNRAS is the only metric in this benchmark whose confidence interval remains above the random-chance threshold ($\text{AUC} > 0.5$), confirming that the variance-stabilization mechanism provides a statistically significant operational gain in vetting efficiency where traditional estimators fail.

The metric exhibits a dual-regime sensitivity to the dispersion contrast ($\psi$). In the stability regime ($\psi < 0.15$), the penalty growth is minimal (Penalty $< 1.15$), preserving the signal-to-noise integrity of confirmed planetary candidates. Conversely, in the anomalous regime ($\psi > 0.60$), the logarithmic term induces a necessary saturation effect, suppressing the significance of high-variance artifacts. This segregation is empirically confirmed in the penalty spectrum shown in Figure \ref{fig:penalty_dist}. The population clearly bifurcates into a dominant mode of stable targets and a sparse "long-tail" of heteroscedastic anomalies, providing a robust statistical foundation for our proposed three-tier classification system.

