\section{Discussion and Comparative Framework} \label{sec:discussion}

The empirical results presented in Section \ref{sec:performance} reveal a distinct hierarchy in vetting efficiency, with Log-SNRAS achieving the highest AUC of \textbf{0.744} compared to the baseline T-SNR (0.594) and the robust estimator R-SNR (0.441). In this section, we analyze the statistical mechanisms driving this performance, the implications of the "inverse performance" phenomenon, and the metric's operational role in future surveys.

\subsection{The Bias-Variance Tradeoff in Vetting}
From a statistical inference perspective, Log-SNRAS functions as a \textit{shrinkage estimator}. Unlike the traditional SNR, which serves as an unbiased estimator of signal significance under Gaussian assumptions, our metric intentionally introduces a negative bias ($\mathcal{B} < 0$) that scales with the stability penalty $\mathcal{P}$.
\begin{equation}
    E[\text{Log-SNRAS}] \approx E[\text{SNR}_{\text{trad}}] - E[\ln(1+\psi)]
\end{equation}

This operational behavior is empirically evident in the diagnostic distributions presented in the complete observational catalog in the Appendix. As detailed in Table \ref{tab:casestudy_summary}, confirmed planetary transits are characterized by lower, more stable score distributions compared to high-amplitude artifacts. For instance, stable confirmed targets maintain scores proximal to their traditional significance, while extreme heteroscedastic outliers undergo substantial score shrinkage due to variance inflation. While this introduces a conservative bias—slightly underestimating the significance of stable signals—it serves a critical operational purpose: it drastically minimizes the \textit{variance} of the False Positive Rate (FPR).

\subsection{Mechanism of Variance Suppression and Inverse Performance}
A critical finding of this study is the "inverse performance" observed in the Robust SNR ($AUC=0.441$), where the metric fell below the random classifier baseline. This counter-intuitive result confirms that traditional robust estimators, by down-weighting outliers without considering local stability, often inadvertently favor high-amplitude non-stationary noise.

To understand why Log-SNRAS succeeds where R-SNR fails, it is crucial to distinguish between the behavior of the final metric and its constituent penalty term. The vetting logic of Log-SNRAS operates on an \textbf{inverse stability relationship}:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{The Penalty Term ($\psi$):} Exhibits a "lower-is-better" behavior. Validated planetary transits cluster at low dispersion contrast values ($\psi \approx 0$), indicating morphological stability across the transit phase.
    \item \textbf{The Final Metric (Log-SNRAS):} Exhibits a "higher-is-better" behavior. By applying a logarithmic penalty proportional to $\psi$, the score of high-variance artifacts is suppressed, effectively separating them from the stable population.
\end{itemize}
Therefore, the bias observed in traditional robust estimators is corrected in Log-SNRAS by strictly penalizing the statistical instability of the artifact rather than just the signal depth.

\subsection{Comparison with Correlated Noise Models}
To contextualize the performance of Log-SNRAS, it is essential to compare it against established red noise correction methods \citep{pont2006}. Log-SNRAS differs fundamentally by operating in the \textit{local stability domain}. By penalizing the dispersion contrast ($\psi$) specifically across the transit boundary, our metric acts as an instantaneous stability filter. As shown in our comparison, Log-SNRAS demonstrates superior selectivity for artifacts like ``rolling bands'' or ``cosmic ray splashes,'' which create extreme local heteroscedasticity without necessarily dominating the global red noise budget.

