\subsection{Complementary Efficiency and Machine Learning Integration} \label{sec:5.5}

\textcolor{blue}{Recent evaluations of classical classifiers on Kepler time-series data \citep{FazelHesar2024} have shown Random Forest achieving 94.2\% accuracy for transit-like signal classification. While supervised classifiers reach high accuracy on balanced datasets, they still require robust pre-vetting to handle heteroscedastic noise \citep{FazelHesar2024b}, a gap that Log-SNRAS directly addresses. Complementary studies using ML to model stellar rotation periods from Kepler photometry \citep{Maxted2018} highlight the growing need for variance-stabilised metrics that can operate upstream of activity-correction pipelines. Rather than serving as a replacement, Log-SNRAS offers a transparent, $\mathcal{O}(N)$ pre-screening layer that allows computationally intensive deep-learning models such as AstroNet or RAVEN to focus on high-fidelity candidates.}

\textcolor{blue}{Furthermore, the differentiable logarithmic penalty structure of Log-SNRAS suggests utility beyond standalone vetting. As suggested by recent peer review, it could be readily incorporated to evaluate the outputs of deep learning approaches or utilized as a custom loss function to train neural networks to natively handle non-stationary and heteroscedastic noise in time-series data.}

\subsection{Independence from Detrending Pipelines} \label{sec:5.4}

The substantial divergence in vetting performance—an AUC of \textbf{0.744} for Log-SNRAS versus \textbf{0.594} for Traditional SNR—confirms that standard depth-based metrics remain highly vulnerable to residual artifacts even after PDC-MAP correction. \textcolor{blue}{While supervised classifiers reach high accuracy on balanced datasets, they still require robust pre-vetting to handle heteroscedastic noise, a gap that Log-SNRAS directly addresses by penalizing the instability that persists in the residual data \citep{FazelHesar2024b}.} Log-SNRAS bridges this gap by providing an instantaneous stability filter that operates independently of the global detrending solution.

\subsection{Limitations and Future Work} \label{sec:limitations}

\textcolor{blue}{While Log-SNRAS demonstrates significant diagnostic advantages, several constraints regarding its current implementation and validation must be acknowledged:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Because the confirmed class is dominated by segments from a single stable host (TIC~261136679), the reported AUC values should be interpreted as proof-of-concept performance estimates on the present curated adversarial benchmark rather than as definitive mission-wide generalization metrics.
    \item Our benchmarking was conducted on a curated adversarial dataset rather than a blind survey sample.
    \item Although we highlight its complementarity to deep-learning architectures, this study does not provide a direct, head-to-head performance comparison with models like AstroNet or RAVEN.
    \item The proposed three-tier thresholds are empirical and dataset-specific, meaning they may require recalibration when applied to surveys with significantly different noise floors or cadences.
    \item The metric is strictly a post-detection vetting filter and requires a known ephemeris to calculate $\sigma_{in}$ and $\sigma_{out}$.
    \item The behavior of the dispersion contrast $\psi$ under extreme correlated red noise or extremely low cadence ($N_{in} < 20$) remains largely unexplored, potentially necessitating bootstrap-based uncertainty quantification in such regimes.
    \item While the current implementation is restricted to MATLAB, the linear $\mathcal{O}(N)$ logic is computationally simple and can be straightforwardly translated into Python or C++ for integration into standard astronomical pipelines.
\end{enumerate}}
