\section{Conclusions} \label{sec:conclusions}

In this work, we introduced the Logarithmic Signal-to-Noise Ratio with Adjusted Statistics (Log-SNRAS), a novel vetting metric specifically engineered to mitigate the impact of heteroscedastic noise and instrumental artifacts in high-precision transit photometry. By integrating a logarithmic stability penalty governed by the dispersion contrast ($\psi$), the metric provides a quantitative measure of signal reliability that transcends traditional depth-based estimators.

Our comprehensive empirical validation across a curated adversarial catalog of 151 \textit{Kepler} and \textit{TESS} targets demonstrates that:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Improved diagnostic performance on the present benchmark:} Log-SNRAS achieves the \textcolor{blue}{highest AUC of 0.744}, significantly outperforming commonly used SNR baselines including P-SNR (0.667) and Traditional SNR (0.594). Crucially, it effectively decouples genuine planetary signals from high-amplitude stellar variability.
    \item \textbf{Robustness Against Inverse Performance:} Unlike the Robust SNR (R-SNR), which succumbed to an "inverse performance" regime ($AUC=0.441$) by favoring non-stationary noise, Log-SNRAS successfully penalized these artifacts, maintaining a strict separation above the random classifier baseline.
    \item \textbf{Preservation of Sensitivity:} Injection tests on active stars (e.g., Pi Mensae) confirm that the logarithmic penalty is selective; it suppresses statistical anomalies without compromising the detection sensitivity for stable super-Earth candidates.
\end{enumerate}

Because the confirmed class is dominated by segments from a single stable host (TIC~261136679), the reported AUC values should be interpreted as proof-of-concept performance estimates on the present curated adversarial benchmark rather than as definitive mission-wide generalization metrics. Broader validation across a multi-host sample is required before operational deployment.

As exoplanet surveys transition towards higher cadence observations and fainter targets, the vulnerability of standard metrics to impulsive noise becomes a critical bottleneck. \textcolor{blue}{Log-SNRAS offers a transparent, $\mathcal{O}(N)$ pre-screening layer that complements computationally intensive deep-learning models such as AstroNet or RAVEN, providing an interpretable and scalable solution for automating the vetting process. By integrating the three-tier classification system into existing pipelines, we estimate that manual vetting efforts can be reduced by 40--60\% in high-noise regimes. For example, Log-SNRAS suppressed the significance of known artifacts such as KIC 8462852 by 69.4\% and KIC 12644769 by 76.8\% while preserving stable planetary signals to within 4.4\%. The correction of the ``inverse performance'' failure—where traditional estimators favor noise over signals—represents the core operational advantage of our method.} 

\textcolor{blue}{By providing a statistically grounded safety filter that penalises variance instability while preserving sensitivity for genuine transits, Log-SNRAS can help future surveys maintain high catalog purity even as data volumes continue to grow.}
