\section{Physical Basis of the Stability Penalty: The Lomax Prior} \label{sec:appendixA}

To establish a rigorous physical basis for the logarithmic penalty term $\mathcal{P}$, we model the variance instability not as arbitrary noise, but as a stochastic variable following a heavy-tailed distribution defined on the positive semi-axis.

\subsection{Why the Lomax Distribution?}
In selecting a prior for the dispersion contrast $\psi = |\sigma_{in} - \sigma_{out}| / \sigma_{out}$, two physical constraints must be satisfied:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Non-Negativity:} Unlike flux residuals which can be negative, the dispersion contrast is strictly non-negative ($\psi \ge 0$). This excludes symmetric heavy-tailed distributions like the Student's $t$ or Cauchy distribution, which are defined on $(-\infty, \infty)$.
    \item \textbf{Heavy Tails:} Instrumental artifacts (e.g., momentum dumps, thermal transients) produce variance outliers that decay slower than an exponential function.
\end{enumerate}
The \textbf{Lomax Distribution} (Pareto Type II) serves as a canonical heavy-tailed distribution on the positive semi-axis that satisfies both conditions. We therefore define $\psi$ as a random variable distributed according to a Lomax prior:
\begin{equation}
    P(\psi | \alpha, \lambda) = \frac{\alpha}{\lambda} \left( 1 + \frac{\psi}{\lambda} \right)^{-(\alpha+1)}, \quad \psi \ge 0
\end{equation}
This prior does not assume that instrumental noise is \textit{exactly} Lomax-distributed; rather, it provides a robust heavy-tailed envelope that captures the empirical power-law behavior of variance outliers observed in high-precision photometry.

\subsection{The Information-Theoretic Penalty}
The metric is constructed to penalize the "surprisal" (self-information) of observing a specific instability level. The information content $\mathcal{I}$ is the negative log-likelihood of the prior:
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{I}(\psi) = - \ln P(\psi) \approx (\alpha+1) \ln \left( 1 + \frac{\psi}{\lambda} \right) + C
\end{equation}
Setting the scale parameter $\lambda=1$ (normalized contrast) and absorbing constants, we recover the functional form of our penalty:
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{P} \propto \ln(1 + \psi)
\end{equation}
\textbf{Conclusion:} The Log-SNRAS metric represents a \textbf{Bayesian-consistent detector} under a Lomax instability prior. This formulation confirms that the logarithmic penalty is not an ad hoc heuristic, but the natural information-theoretic cost for a signal immersed in one-sided, heavy-tailed variance noise.

