\section{Statistical Properties and Asymptotic Limits} \label{sec:appendix_stats}

We rigorously derive the asymptotic behavior of the metric, addressing the unequal sampling between in-transit and out-of-transit regions and providing a formal convergence proof.

\subsection{Sample Size Disparity and Consistency}
In transit photometry, the number of in-transit points ($N_{in}$) is typically much smaller than the out-of-transit baseline ($N_{out}$), i.e., $N_{in} \ll N_{out}$. Consequently, the estimation uncertainty of the dispersion contrast $\psi$ is dominated by the variance of $\hat{\sigma}_{in}$. Since the sample standard deviation $S$ is a consistent estimator of $\sigma$, the convergence rate is determined by the smaller sample size:
\begin{equation}
    (\hat{\sigma}_{in} - \sigma) = O_p(N_{in}^{-1/2}) \quad \text{and} \quad (\hat{\sigma}_{out} - \sigma) = O_p(N_{out}^{-1/2})
\end{equation}
Given $N_{in} \ll N_{out}$, the combined contrast scales as:
\begin{equation}
    \psi = \frac{|\hat{\sigma}_{in} - \hat{\sigma}_{out}|}{\hat{\sigma}_{out}} = O_p(N_{in}^{-1/2})
\end{equation}
Thus, as long as the transit duration ensures sufficient sampling ($N_{in} \gtrsim 30$), the penalty term converges in probability to zero under the null hypothesis ($H_0$).

\subsection{Formal Proof via Slutsky's Theorem}
We seek the asymptotic distribution of the test statistic:
\begin{equation}
    Z = \text{Log-SNRAS} = \frac{\text{SNR}_{trad}}{1 + \mathcal{P}}
\end{equation}
Under $H_0$, we have established two conditions:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item By the Central Limit Theorem (for $N_{in} \gg 1$), the numerator converges in distribution:
    \begin{equation}
        X_n = \text{SNR}_{trad} \xrightarrow{d} \mathcal{N}(0, 1)
    \end{equation}
    \item By the consistency of the variance estimators, the penalty term in the denominator converges in probability:
    \begin{equation}
        \mathcal{P} \xrightarrow{p} 0 \implies Y_n = (1 + \mathcal{P}) \xrightarrow{p} 1
    \end{equation}
\end{enumerate}
Invoking \textbf{Slutsky's Theorem}, which states that if $X_n \xrightarrow{d} X$ and $Y_n \xrightarrow{p} c$ (where $c$ is a constant), then $X_n/Y_n \xrightarrow{d} X/c$, we obtain:
\begin{equation}
    Z \xrightarrow{d} \frac{\mathcal{N}(0, 1)}{1} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1)
\end{equation}
\textbf{Implication:} The Log-SNRAS metric preserves the standard Gaussian false alarm rates asymptotically. This allows the use of established detection thresholds (e.g., $7.1\sigma$) without requiring recalibration tables for different noise environments, provided the signal is homoscedastic.

\subsection{Bias Quantification with Implicit Correlation}
The introduction of the penalty creates a bias $\mathcal{B}$ for heteroscedastic signals.
\begin{equation}
    \mathcal{B} \approx - E[\text{SNR}_{trad} \cdot \mathcal{P}]
\end{equation}
This expectation accounts for the implicit dependence between the SNR (derived from mean flux) and $\mathcal{P}$ (derived from flux variance), both computed from the same realization. The resulting \textit{Negative Shrinkage Bias} is a designed feature that acts as a soft-thresholding operator for vetting reliability.
